'@apollo/client';> \nContributor> \n@coderabbitai> \ncoderabbitai bot> \n5 days ago> \n🧹 Nitpick | 🔵 Trivial> \n> \nShared InMemoryCache across tests may leak Apollo state> \n> \nUsing a single module‑scope const cache = new InMemoryCache() and passing it into nearly every <MockedProvider cache={cache}> means all tests share one Apollo cache instance. If UploadPluginModal (now or in future changes) performs real GraphQL operations, writes from one test can affect subsequent tests via cached data.> \n> \nA more isolated pattern is to create a fresh cache per render/helper, e.g. cache={new InMemoryCache()} or a small renderWithProvider helper that instantiates a new cache each time. Using `--no-verify` bypasses the pre-commit hooks, which include:\n\n- **ESLint** (code quality checks)\n- **TypeScript** (type checking) \n- **Prettier** (code formatting)\n- **Tests** (ensuring nothing breaks)\n\nThese hooks are there for good reasons - they maintain code quality.
